<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-683-662  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 683 662.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  July 16 1990 n278 p26(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>New weapons in drug wars. (automation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Forsythe, Jason.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Office of National Drug Control Policy (ONDCP) is working onthe problem of sharing information among the many agencies and lawenforcement groups with which it cooperates.andP;  Centralizingdrug-related information has been difficult due to differentsystems, slow bureaucracies, and privacy concerns.andP;  The DrugEnforcement Agency (DEA) is updating equipment by installing 2,000high-speed Unisys Corp workstations in its 19 divisions by the endof 1990.andP;  The most sophisticated and promising informationtechnology (IT) project is being undertaken by the TreasuryDepartment, which tries to catch money launderers.andP;  Its FinancialCrimes Enforcement Network (Fincen) is rewriting an artificialintelligent system as a relational database.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Drug AbuseLaw EnforcementAutomationInformation Resources ManagementUnited States. Office of National Drug Control Policy.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographchart.andO;Caption:   Agency information flowchart. (chart)Agencies of the organized crime and drug enforcement task force.andO;(chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>